-- в”Ђв”Ђ 99designs в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$A design marketplace, now part of Vista, that connects businesses with freelance designers through design contests and one-to-one projects for logos, branding, packaging, and web design.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Logo design contest packages start around 299 USD (Bronze tier)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2008, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Melbourne, Australia (now operating as part of Vista, headquartered in Waltham, Massachusetts, United States)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$99designs Review 2026: Pricing, How It Works and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Understand how 99designs' design contests and 1-to-1 projects work, including pricing packages, pros and cons, and how it compares to other design platforms.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$99designs is a design-focused freelance marketplace founded in 2008 in Melbourne, Australia, by Matt Mickiewicz and Mark Harbottle as a spin-off of the SitePoint community. Unlike general freelance marketplaces such as Fiverr or Upwork that cover many categories of work, 99designs focuses exclusively on graphic design, including logos, brand identity, web and app design, packaging, illustration, and print materials. The platform was acquired by Vista (the parent company of Vistaprint) in 2020 and rebranded as 99designs by Vista in 2022, giving it access to Vista's broader small-business customer base and print-production capabilities. 99designs offers two main ways to work with designers: design contests, where a client posts a brief and multiple designers submit competing concepts before the client selects a winner and pays a fixed package price, and 1-to-1 projects, where a client works directly with a single hand-picked designer on an hourly or fixed-fee basis, similar to a traditional freelance engagement. The contest model is 99designs' signature offering: clients choose a package tier (commonly Bronze, Silver, Gold, and Platinum) that determines how many designers can participate, how many initial concepts are delivered, and which skill tier of designers can enter (with higher tiers restricted to Mid-level or Top-rated designers). Pricing varies by category; logo design contests are among the most affordable, starting around 299 USD for a Bronze package and rising to roughly 1,299 USD for a Platinum package with maximum design volume and top-tier designer access. Categories like product packaging design and logo-plus-brand-identity packages carry higher price points, often ranging from roughly 449 USD to 2,499 USD depending on tier. All contest packages include full copyright transfer and production-ready files upon completion. 99designs also offers a money-back guarantee model where clients can request a refund if they are not satisfied with any of the submitted concepts, reducing the financial risk of the contest format. Because payment is tied to a specific package price rather than a recurring subscription, 99designs functions more like a project marketplace than a SaaS product, though it operates a persistent web platform, in-app messaging, and file management tools that support ongoing collaboration between clients and designers throughout a project.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2606bcee-7c10-4c19-ac05-38743faafbbd';

