-- в”Ђв”Ђ Abby в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$An open-source, type-safe feature flagging, remote config, and A/B testing service built for developers, with SDKs for React, Next.js, Svelte, Remix, and Angular.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free plan available; paid plans start at 12 USD per month per project$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Abby (tryabby.com) Review 2026: Pricing, Features and Setup$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$See how Abby's open-source feature flags, remote config, and A/B testing tools work for developers, including pricing plans, features, pros and cons.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Abby, built by the team behind tryabby.com, is a developer-focused feature flagging, remote configuration, and A/B testing service. It is fully open source, with its code published on GitHub, and offers a self-hosting option in addition to its hosted SaaS product, which appeals to development teams that want control over where their flagging and testing data lives. The company describes the product as having emerged from an engineer's internal frustration with existing feature flag tooling, and positions itself against larger, more enterprise-oriented experimentation platforms by focusing specifically on developer experience: fully type-safe SDKs, first-class support for modern JavaScript frameworks (React, Next.js, Svelte and SvelteKit, Remix, and Angular), server-side rendering and static site generation compatibility, and browser devtools for debugging flag and remote-config values directly in context. Abby's core primitives are feature flags (boolean toggles that can be switched on or off from a dashboard to control feature visibility or roll back problematic releases), remote config (dynamically adjustable configuration values that don't require a redeploy to change), and A/B tests (experiments that can be layered on top of flags or config values to measure the impact of different variants). Flags and experiments can be scoped using multiple environments and refined with user segments and conditional targeting rules, so different users or user groups can see different flag states. Abby markets itself on privacy: it states that it does not track personalized user data and does not use marketing cookies, and that all hosted data is stored in Europe, which may appeal to teams with GDPR or data residency requirements. Pricing follows a freemium, per-project model rather than a flat organization-wide fee: a Free plan includes a capped number of monthly events, one A/B test, three feature flags or remote config values, and five environments; a Starter plan at 12 USD per month per project offers the same limits as Free but as a paid, presumably more fully-featured, tier; a Startup plan at 89 USD per month per project scales up to 10,000 events per month, 10 A/B tests, and 30 feature flags or remote configs; and Pro and Enterprise tiers are available on request for teams needing higher event volumes, unlimited flags and tests, or additional environments. As a smaller, developer-tool-oriented company relative to established players like LaunchDarkly, Split, or Optimizely, Abby is best suited to individual developers, small engineering teams, and startups that want lightweight, type-safe feature flagging without enterprise sales overhead, rather than large organizations running complex, cross-functional experimentation programs.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2a6a3a09-2391-4c68-b426-c1902814f2f3';

